name: Madison de Rozario
summary: Australian Paralympic wheelchair racer Madison de Rozario has endured an emotional rollercoaster at the Paris Paralympics. On the day of the opening ceremony, she received the tragic news that her father had passed away. Despite her grief, de Rozario forged ahead, competing in the marathon and winning a silver medal. She has since spoken out about the toll her father's death took on her mentally and emotionally, revealing that she considered withdrawing from the Games. However, she ultimately decided to compete in his honor and share her story to inspire others.

Visitors can now also enjoy morning yoga and wellness walks within the tranquil zoo environment. name: Lee Carsley
summary: England's interim manager Lee Carsley has become a focal point of controversy due to his decision not to sing either the English or Irish national anthems before a match between England and the Republic of Ireland. Carsley, who is an Irish-born former player and current coach for England, explained that his choice stems from his desire to remain impartial in the politically charged atmosphere of the match. This decision has sparked debates about national identity, loyalty, and the complex relationship between the two nations. Some commentators have criticized Carsley for not showing sufficient respect to England, while others have defended his right to express his personal beliefs. The controversy has highlighted the often-sensitive nature of national symbols and the challenges of balancing personal convictions with the expectations of a nation.
